This is using:
- ClickHouse client version 18.14.11.
- Connected to ClickHouse server version 18.14.11 revision 54409.

Currently when running queries over the http interface and requesting the http progress headers there is no easy way to tell that the query finished executing 100% or something went wrong.
For example when the query fails half way the response would look something like this:

```
`
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"159466057","read_bytes":"23600976436","total_rows":"240828416"}
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"161055305","read_bytes":"23836185140","total_rows":"240828416"}
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"162456137","read_bytes":"24043508276","total_rows":"240828416"}
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"164045385","read_bytes":"24278716980","total_rows":"240828416"}
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"165438025","read_bytes":"24484827700","total_rows":"240828416"}

Code: 241, e.displayText() = DB::Exception: Memory limit (for query) exceeded: ...`

```
While a successful result would look something like this:
```
`
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"1340919","read_bytes":"437228836","total_rows":"1417216"}
X-ClickHouse-Progress: {"read_rows":"1365495","read_bytes":"445829218","total_rows":"1417216"}
 
{
	"meta":
	[
		{
			"name": "sleep(3)",
			"type": "UInt8"
		},
		{
....
`
```

The only way to tell if it succeeded would be to see if the body content contains `e.displayText() = DB::Exception` or some other string, but this is not reliable in the long run.

It would be really helpful to add a final header which denotes success/failure or even just ensuring that the `X-ClickHouse-Progress` is sent for the last part of the query., so that the `read_rows` is equal with the `total_rows`.

```
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS test_alter;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS test_alter_agg;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS test_alter_mv;

CREATE TABLE test_alter (a Int8) ENGINE = MergeTree() partition by tuple() order by tuple();

CREATE TABLE test_alter_agg (a Int8) ENGINE = MergeTree() partition by tuple() order by tuple();

CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW test_alter_mv TO test_alter_agg AS SELECT a FROM test_alter;

INSERT INTO test_alter VALUES (1);

SELECT * FROM test_alter_mv;
```

Works ok so far. Not let's add a column:

```ALTER TABLE test_alter ADD COLUMN c Int8;

ALTER TABLE test_alter_agg ADD COLUMN c Int8;

DETACH TABLE test_alter_mv;

ATTACH MATERIALIZED VIEW test_alter_mv TO test_alter_agg AS SELECT a,c from test_alter;

SHOW CREATE TABLE test_alter_mv

statement
 CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW test.test_alter_mv TO test.test_alter_agg ( a Int8) AS SELECT a FROM test.test_alter  


1 rows in set. Elapsed: 0.002 sec. 
```

MV definition is not updated after ATTACH. It keeps using the old one without column 'c'.

```
INSERT INTO test_alter VALUES(1,2);

Received exception from server (version 1.1.54394):
Code: 10. DB::Exception: Received from localhost:9000, ::1. DB::Exception: Expected column c: while pushing to view test.test_alter_mv. 
```

DROP/CREATE MV works, but it requires to fill the structure. It also works if structure is specified in ATTACH. But it is confusing that ClickHouse does not pick up structure from underlying SELECT statement and uses the old one here, while it works fine in other cases.
